Don&rsquo;t be a lemon. Seriously, no one wants to be a lemon, but a lot of people are! A lemon describes someone or something that is defective or not useful. The Christian life often gets mistaken for simply a list of &ldquo;don&rsquo;ts&rdquo;:
&lt;ul&gt;
 	&lt;li&gt;Don&rsquo;t watch this show.&lt;/li&gt;
 	&lt;li&gt;Don&rsquo;t say that word.&lt;/li&gt;
 	&lt;li&gt;Don&rsquo;t be mean to others.&lt;/li&gt;
 	&lt;li&gt;Don&rsquo;t punt that kitten&hellip;wait what?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
The Christian life is SO much more. We have been invited into God&rsquo;s story, welcomed into His Kingdom, and called a son or daughter to DO things for the glory of Christ. In John 15 Jesus tells His followers, &ldquo;I chose you and appointed you that you should go and bear fruit and that your fruit should abide (16).&rdquo; If you are a follower of Jesus, then you have been chosen and appointed to bear fruit. Now, what does it mean to bear fruit? Fruit is the results of your actions and as a result good fruit only comes from those who abide (rest, live, obey, trust) in Christ (John 15:4-5).

The Christian life is not a useless or defective life, rather is one that is seen by the fruit our lives bear. &lt;em&gt;Produce&lt;/em&gt; aims to teach students the importance of living a life that glorifies God by producing the fruit of the Spirit.

