Description:
When you read through the Gospel accounts in Scripture, you inevitably encounter a parable and ask the question, &ldquo;Why does Jesus teach like this?&rdquo; Around one-third of Jesus&rsquo; teaching is in parables. Parables seem to trip every reader up and not only wonder &lt;em&gt;why&lt;/em&gt; Jesus taught like this, but &lt;em&gt;what&lt;/em&gt; Jesus meant by His parables. If you have ever wanted a deeper understanding of Jesus&rsquo; parables, then this is a great starting point for you to begin understanding and applying the great parables of Jesus Christ.

&lt;u&gt;What&rsquo;s a parable?&lt;/u&gt;

A parable has a very broad meaning in Scripture. A parable can be a proverb (Luke 4:23), a riddle (Mk 3:23), a comparison (Mt 13:33), a contrast (Lk 18:1&ndash;8) and both simple stories (Lk 13:6&ndash;9) and complex stories (Mt 22:1&ndash;14). This broad term is used by Jesus as his primary way on teaching about the Kingdom of God, or heaven, and the character of God. A parable is characterized by an example that elicits thought by placing examples side by side to illustrate a point.

SERIES OVERVIEW
&lt;ul&gt;
 	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Parable of the Sower&lt;/strong&gt; // Matthew 13:10-13&lt;/li&gt;
 	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Parable of the Prodigal Son&lt;/strong&gt; // Matthew 13:34; Mark 4:34&lt;/li&gt;
 	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Parable of the Sower&lt;/strong&gt; // Mark 4:11; Luke 8:10&lt;/li&gt;
 	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Parable of the Tower Builder and Warring King&lt;/strong&gt; // Luke 12:41&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
